metadata.name: The Visual Code #1
metadata.description:
The Visual Code is a collection of generative art that celebrates the jazzy, dynamic visuals inspired by Wassily Kandinsky, Jackson Pollock, Kazimir Malevich, Joan Miro and The Dave Brubeck Quartet's music.

Each piece uniquely expresses the artist's creativity and technical skill, showcasing the beauty and complexity of computer-generated visuals.

As a codegen artist, I am constantly in awe of the boundless potential of generative art. The ability to create unique, one-of-a-kind pieces using code is truly fascinating to me.

Generative art allows for a level of artistic expression that is simply not possible with traditional mediums. Using algorithms and mathematical principles allows for creating complex, dynamic visuals that are constantly evolving and changing.

What I find particularly interesting about generative art is its focus on the creation process. Rather than simply producing a static, finished product, the artist is more concerned with the journey and the process of creating the art. This allows for experimentation and exploration that is impossible in more traditional forms of art.

In my own work, I strive to push the boundaries of generative art and explore new possibilities. I constantly experiment with different algorithms and techniques to create something new and unique.

I am excited to continue learning and growing as an artist and to see where my passion for generative art will take me.

The collection is a tribute to the art of coding and its endless possibilities for artistic expression. From mesmerizing geometric patterns to pulsating colour fields, each piece in the collection is a testament to the endless potential of code as a medium for artistic creation.

Previous collectors are automatically on the reserve list for this exclusive collection. This is a rare opportunity to own a piece of generative art that captures the imagination and celebrates the beauty of code.

Press [S] to save.

metadata.name: Rapport #109
metadata.description:
The concept of nexus is a powerful one. It speaks to the idea that everything is related and that each part is necessary to create the whole. Rapport is about the relationship these parts have, harmonious or discordant, to convey a sense of unity and purpose. You are invited to explore the details and interactions of each object in its surroundings, recognizing the immense value they all have in building greater things.

A few shortcuts are available in live mode:
1 : Toggle the view (fit screen / original size)
T : Toggle paper texture
S : Save current view
H : Re-render in high resolution

The piece might require high processing power depending on its features. A good desktop or laptop running chrome is recommended.

Created with p5.js and GLSL
dmarchi, 2023.

metadata.name: Errance #180
metadata.description:
Errance - an exploration of abstract and digital glitch fusion. The algorithm crafts the concept and structure, while randomness navigates the detailed textures, exploring the interplay between systematic design and the unforeseen aspects of randomness. Errance represents a journey of discovery, one without a defined endpoint, capturing the unexpected and fortuitous outcomes that emerge as algorithms navigate freely, leaving a trail of unique and unpredictable patterns.

Best experienced in live mode at high resolution, the outputs vary significantly due to multiple features, occasionally favouring a slightly asymmetric balance. Under the hood, the algorithm employs a combination of recursive functions, 3D primitives, and multiple textures derived from trigonometric and noise functions using p5.js. Last but not least, during rendering, the outputs are enhanced by one of several versions of a GLSL shader.

In live mode:
-press 1 to save a 2K-resolution PNG copy.
-press 2 for a 4K-resolution PNG copy.
-press 3 to render a version without passepartout.
-press 4 for a 2k-resolution PNG copy without passepartout.
-press 5 for a 4k-resolution PNG copy without passepartout.

metadata.name: Blurevich #310
metadata.description:
"Blurevich"

The painting is characterized by its non-representational style, where the rectangles are not meant to depict recognizable objects or figures. 
Instead, the blurred rectangles serve as visual elements that create a sense of movement and dynamism in the painting. 
The use of blurriness in the rectangles gives the painting a hazy and ethereal quality. 
The colors used in the painting would  be bold and striking, creating a striking contrast between the sharp edges of the rectangles and the soft, blurred edges. 
The overall effect of the painting is one of abstraction and experimentation, express our emotions.

metadata.name: Poema #170
metadata.description:
A poem is sometimes clear and colorful. 
It can be sharp. 
It can be oneiric. 
Sometimes it is enigmatic and deep.

The starting point of this project is an investigation of typography. The construction of a visual poem without words. Where letters and other signs evoke movement, rhythm, sound, echo and silence. The work plays with processes of construction/deconstruction of characters, with the visibility or subtlety of typographic elements.

*'Poema' is part of the 'Visual Poetry' group show curated by Atelier (http://atelierart.io).

----------------------------------
Each iteration has:
-> an alternative version in Portrait format, activated by the [p] key
-> a meta-poem, built from the features' metadata, accessible in the browser console, activated by the [F12] key

----------------------------------
Features:
-> Encruzilhada (Crossroad) = 2 possibilities
-> 3 types of Reverberations 
-> 6 types of Luminescences 
-> 5 Color schemes
-> 14 Palettes 

* The names of the palettes pay homage to poets and artists who deal with the visuality of writing in their work. 7 palettes honor women, 7 palettes honor men. Almost all from Latin America.

----------control keys------------ 
[F12] access to the meta-poem on browser console 
----------------------------------
[p] alternate format portrait/square 
[o] border on/off 
[e] save image with 2000 pixels height
[m] save image with 4000 pixels height
[a] save image with actual size
----------------------------------
Depending on the size option, the render time can be long.

----------------------------------
Created with p5.js
Tested in Chrome and Firefox on both Windows and Mac OS.

metadata.name: Dialog Box #129
metadata.description:
Dialog Box is a playful generative art project that invites viewers to engage with the concept of choice in the digital age. Inspired by the early Mac OS, the artwork presents an interface of two buttons, each symbolizing a choice steeped in 80s and 90s pop culture, from the serious to the lighthearted.

https://medium.com/@duaneking/dialog-box-by-duane-king-scott-brewer-and-adam-moliski-abab7afd3519

metadata.name: RGB Elementary Cellular Automaton #533
metadata.description:
Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton where 3 different rules are drawn in the Red, Green and Blue color components of the image.

Rules are selected randomly among a pre-selection of 53 rules from which nice behaviors emerge.

Tokens can have a cell size in the [1; 20] range.

metadata.name: Universal Rayhatcher #547
metadata.description:
# What is this?

This is 6942 characters of highly experimental code.

This is a version of my rayhatcher framework (see https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/rayhatching-evolution) that can do literally everything. Or, at least anything you can do within 512 characters of Javascript code. Which is slightly more than a mortal brain can comprehend.

This is my answer to the question: What is the least restrictive set of parameters for fx(params)?

# Should I be minting this?

Depends if you know and like building SDF formulas. Otherwise probably not. Like I said, this is highly experimental code. But it's definitely worth checking the collection and/or secondary for cool stuff that is already minted.

# How does it work?

The minter designs an SDF (Signed Distance Function) which is rendered using my rayhatcher algorithm. They then use the SDF formula in the SDF Code parameter. It's not very complicated, just efficient.

You can press "h" to load the documentation and read about how everything works. Or you can press "d" to read the dev docs. 

# Anything else?

Don't forget that the "Title Seed" param also becomes the "Title" feature of the mint, so make it count.

The params, including the SDF code actually get saved on-chain. Even better, all params and the entire code required to reproduce the image are included in the SVG when saved. See https://twitter.com/piterpasma/status/1649071912742420482 .

(c) 2023 by Piter Pasma // https://piterpasma.nl

metadata.name: √∞olmen #11
metadata.description:
√∞olmen is a generative art project by Diego Pintos.
It draws rectangles with points instead a plain color or border. With some variations in the distribution of this points, we get a kind of noise depth effect.

12 carefully selected palettes. Based in Art Masterpieces and in Nature.
¬∑ Gioconda (Leonardo da Vinci)
¬∑ Guernika (Pablo Picasso)
¬∑ Nighthawks (Edward Hopper)
¬∑ Meninas (Diego Velazquez)
¬∑ Judith beheading Holofernes (Caravaggio)
¬∑ Al Siq (nature)
¬∑ guacamayo (nature)
¬∑ Salamanca (nature)
¬∑ mostaza (nature)
¬∑ Timanfaya (nature)
¬∑ piedra (nature)
¬∑ firefall (nature)

√∞olmen builds 10 compositions:
¬∑ Square
¬∑ PersonChen's Style
¬∑ Equilibrium
¬∑ Hanging
¬∑ Pyramid
¬∑ Row
¬∑ Column
¬∑ 3 columns (randomly aligned)
¬∑ 3 rows (randomly aligned)
¬∑ Frame

Density
¬∑ Tiny: Less than 35 rects. Rare
¬∑ Small: Less than 100 rects. Common.
¬∑ Medium: Less than 250 rects. Common.
¬∑ High: Less than 350 rects. Common.
¬∑ Massive: Less than 500 rects. Rare.
¬∑ Ultra: More than 500 rects. Rarest.

Rarities
¬∑ Rectangle filling type: Filled (95%) or unfilled (5%)
¬∑ Monochrome: Just black and white. Always unfilled. (1%)
¬∑ Dark mode: Dark background (20%). Dark mode can be monochrome.
¬∑ Habitable (90%). See humans later.

Humans
√∞olmen can host tiny humans. Contains a little code that draws humans looking down, in order to to provide size perspective.

Minting
Each √∞olmen contains all rarities inside. As a √∞olmen collector, you can display your final piece in all available formats, and rarity owners can display the regular filled composition. In addition, this can help if you want to print one or more formats.

Tricks and Keys
√∞olmen is responsive, you can zoom out your browser window and refresh to get a larger output.
's' save the current canvas
'd' toggle dark mode
'f' toggle fill mode
'm' toggle monochrome

More info and visual description:
https://thelirios.com/dolmen/

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0
